    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Silent Like the Forests</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Michael Fuerstein letter on Clinton administration plan to limit roadbuilding in national forests says protection of irreplaceable national treasure outweighs momentary benefits (July 5 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Idaho, a Howl Against Roadless Forests'' (news article, July 5):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''In Idaho, a Howl Against Roadless Forests'' (news article, July 5):</p>
        <p>Opponents of the Clinton administration's plan to prohibit future roadbuilding on the remaining roadless parts of national forest land are right to characterize such prohibition as an assault on their way of life.</p>
        <p>But it is unclear why this characterization offers a compelling argument against the protection of an irreplaceable national treasure. The fact that a way of life is entrenched or economically vital speaks only of its sociological function, not of its larger virtue.  One need only consider our history of slavery to recognize this fact.</p>
        <p>The important question is whether the momentary benefits of unrestricted deforestation could ever outweigh the lasting costs. In response to this question, the timber industry seems eerily silent.</p>
        <p>MICHAEL FUERSTEIN  Somerville, Mass., July 5, 2000</p>
      </block>
